Hayek (1945) argues that market-determined prices were essential for a society to make use
of the knowledge possessed by individuals. He makes frequent reference to the inability of
economists, planners, or "a single mind" to calculate market prices. What is important in prices
"is knowledge of the kind which by its nature cannot enter into statistics and therefore cannot be
conveyed to any central authority in statistical form." (p. 524)  <fpage>524</fpage>
               </mixed-citation>
            </p>
